Then you put on the glasses, and the proportions

249
00:17:17,744 --> 00:17:18,765
are now almost OK.

250
00:17:20,227 --> 00:17:22,969
At the end, the main objective is not to bump up

251
00:17:23,590 --> 00:17:24,491
against the characters.

252
00:17:28,592 --> 00:17:33,396
We have lately some good examples of games with incredible cinematic sequences,

253
00:17:33,716 --> 00:17:36,539
no matter if they are first-person shooters or third-person shooters.

254
00:17:37,740 --> 00:17:42,224
In our gameplay, we don't have cameras or singular points of view.

255
00:17:43,285 --> 00:17:48,430
The player is free to go and decide from where he would enjoy the story.

256
00:17:49,511 --> 00:17:54,235
So as well as in theaters, we need to create larger environments, even exaggerated.

257
00:17:56,323 --> 00:18:00,566
And we aim to create comfortable spaces without obstacles.

258
00:18:02,567 --> 00:18:05,909
Another VR-related concern, the textures.

259
00:18:07,370 --> 00:18:09,011
As environment artists, we are worried about

260
00:18:09,372 --> 00:18:11,453
those tiny details on the assets.

261
00:18:13,194 --> 00:18:16,396
But it is a point that when the VR blurriness

262
00:18:16,616 --> 00:18:20,939
and low resolution don't let you appreciate the props

263
00:18:21,159 --> 00:18:24,101
when they are too close to the camera, well, to your eyes.

264
00:18:27,747 --> 00:18:32,949
We have to decide what is worth it and to find more pleasant designs.

265
00:18:36,331 --> 00:18:41,152
We are all glad of using the Allegory Smith tools for the textures creation.

266
00:18:41,953 --> 00:18:46,614
With Perforce linked to them we can share all the new materials and effects in seconds.

267
00:18:47,895 --> 00:18:54,377
And on stylized games like this, sharing base materials between the artists like a wood generator.

268
00:18:55,756 --> 00:19:01,118
We believe it's suitable for achieving a good consistency between the different assets.

269
00:19:04,080 --> 00:19:09,002
The rain, a feature created by Norman Scar, a technical artist.

270
00:19:10,303 --> 00:19:12,964
The rain is made out of a single static mesh.

271
00:19:15,045 --> 00:19:17,126
I guess you don't appreciate the...

272
00:19:19,408 --> 00:19:21,889
Well, you have a better representation on the right side.

273
00:19:23,549 --> 00:19:28,311
Pivot point positions for each raindrop are stored as paired attributes.

274
00:19:29,231 --> 00:19:32,772
And the shader makes sure that they follow the camera properly.

275
00:19:33,972 --> 00:19:38,834
Everything is handled in the GPU to free up the CPU from updating the raindrops every frame.

276
00:19:40,134 --> 00:19:46,336
And a depth texture is also used in order to avoid the rain to clip indoors.

277
00:19:49,875 --> 00:19:55,156
We take that depth texture to reposition the tree leaves on the exterior floors.

278
00:19:57,637 --> 00:20:00,337
This tool was created by Mario Palmero, lead programmer.

279
00:20:01,197 --> 00:20:06,898
I'm glad you're here on this talk because he's currently having another talk in another room.

280
00:20:06,958 --> 00:20:07,899
He's also another speaker.

281
00:20:11,539 --> 00:20:14,600
Well, the rain came with some consequences.

282
00:20:15,660 --> 00:20:17,140
For example, the water drops on the glass.

283
00:20:18,775 --> 00:20:21,916
But before, the technical artist found another issue.

284
00:20:22,476 --> 00:20:27,198
At the time, Unreal for glass solution was very expensive

285
00:20:27,538 --> 00:20:33,001
and it requires to compute the entire PBR shader to achieve some reflection in the glass.

286
00:20:34,501 --> 00:20:38,043
That reflection, however, was a cubemap with no parallax correction

287
00:20:39,123 --> 00:20:42,705
and a less physically correct but way cheaper.

288
00:20:43,242 --> 00:20:46,703
A better looking solution was to completely drop the PBR shader,

289
00:20:47,823 --> 00:20:50,304
sampling the cubemap in an unlit shader,

290
00:20:50,364 --> 00:20:51,764
and do the parallax correction there.

291
00:20:53,524 --> 00:20:54,164
Technical stuff.

292
00:20:56,045 --> 00:20:57,905
Having more control over this also

293
00:20:57,925 --> 00:21:02,206
allow us to sample two different cubemaps for the glass window.

294
00:21:02,226 --> 00:21:06,707
So a different cubemap was seen depending

295
00:21:07,007 --> 00:21:09,307
on which side of the glass you were looking through.

296
00:21:11,924 --> 00:21:16,988
One more time, Substance Designer allowed me to create a procedural texture to extend

297
00:21:17,288 --> 00:21:17,869
the water drops.

298
00:21:20,491 --> 00:21:26,455
The rain is one of the special effects we have in-game, but all the performance issues

299
00:21:26,515 --> 00:21:33,340
and limitations make it impossible to use real-time simulations or particles.

300
00:21:34,363 --> 00:21:37,465
So both two FX artists working on our project,

301
00:21:37,505 --> 00:21:40,328
Simon Trampler and Simon Remes, two Simons,

302
00:21:41,689 --> 00:21:44,211
choose the vertex shader animations

303
00:21:44,271 --> 00:21:45,452
in almost every situation.

304
00:21:46,372 --> 00:21:50,476
For example, the fire sparks and how the rain is affecting

305
00:21:50,496 --> 00:21:53,678
the character temporarily, not only the hair, also

306
00:21:54,359 --> 00:21:56,100
the skin or the clothes.

307
00:21:58,942 --> 00:22:02,605
And more limitations, this time with the expensive volumetric

308
00:22:02,665 --> 00:22:02,845
lights.

309
00:22:04,128 --> 00:22:07,049
The effects artist managed to use planes with transparency

310
00:22:07,109 --> 00:22:11,409
at a fade assort instance.

311
00:22:11,469 --> 00:22:13,950
But we have dense shader complexity issues

312
00:22:13,970 --> 00:22:15,310
that you can see on the right side.

313
00:22:16,030 --> 00:22:19,611
That's why we environment artists avoid and almost forget

314
00:22:20,411 --> 00:22:23,532
about the using of alpha on all our textures on the assets.

315
00:22:26,793 --> 00:22:27,433
The platforms.

316
00:22:28,193 --> 00:22:31,514
Something we enjoy a lot was designing the controllers

317
00:22:31,554 --> 00:22:33,314
for the different VR platforms.

318
00:22:36,101 --> 00:22:43,268
That was the Vive one, here's the Oculus one, all of them with a soft cyberpunk influence and all materials.

319
00:22:45,531 --> 00:22:56,382
And as you can see, we added more functional features to them, like a clock or a laser emitter, related to the teleport feature.

320
00:22:59,664 --> 00:23:08,971
Well, the artists, this is an announced project and I'm not allowed to show more stuff or talk about the story,

321
00:23:09,651 --> 00:23:16,616
but I can say that the story is full of science fiction and this has been a very fun experience for us, the artists.

322
00:23:18,978 --> 00:23:24,862
You catch the objects with your hands and you can easily get hypnotized by the light reflections.

323
00:23:26,383 --> 00:23:28,745
This is also appropriate for the inclusion of aesthetics,

324
00:23:29,045 --> 00:23:30,325
so you can hide them on the assets

325
00:23:30,385 --> 00:23:33,707
and challenge the player to find them.

326
00:23:33,827 --> 00:23:37,589
Well, as conclusion, VR is a beautiful experience

327
00:23:37,729 --> 00:23:42,671
and a perfect place for admiring and showing our own creations.

